replies.bodyText:
The reason we redundantly check if Debug/Trace levels are enabled outside the logging methods is to avoid argument evaluation which is done unconditionally and may have quite noticeable overhead.
Introducing an intermediate convenience method apparently defeats the purpose.

Good point, I will remove it, it looks like org.apache.log4j.Category#debug(java.lang.Object) itself it doing the check again:
   public void debug(Object message) {
        if (!this.repository.isDisabled(10000)) {
            if (Level.DEBUG.isGreaterOrEqual(this.getEffectiveLevel())) {
                this.forcedLog(FQCN, Level.DEBUG, message, (Throwable)null);
            }

        }
    }

If the cost of evaluation is considerable, maybe we should extend the implementation and add a new version of debug which accepts a vararg and does the evaluation only inside the if branch, i.e. something like this:
    public void debug(String format, Object... args ) {
        if (!this.repository.isDisabled(10000)) {
            if (Level.DEBUG.isGreaterOrEqual(this.getEffectiveLevel())) {
                this.forcedLog(FQCN, Level.DEBUG, String.format(format, args), (Throwable)null);
            }
        }
    }



The existing trace() method doesn't conform to that principle and should be reworked (separately from this PR; also to use Logger). It should not be considered as acceptable still.

Yes, I also think we should change trace() to use our Logger but I would do it separately since it is orthogonal to this change.

